CHECKLIST COMMENTS: With Duanpen Passant
SPECIES COMMENTS: This was my 6th or 7th trip to PJNY searching for BB Pitta.  My earlier trips had all been with Paul Farrell and were part of a broader team effort to find BB Pitta in NE Thailand, details of which are documented in the June 20203 issue of BirdingAsia (being published currently).----On several earlier trips Paul F had made sound recordings and had seen the bird, although I had not, but so far we had not managed a photograph. ----On this visit, with Duanpen Passant, I was finally able to see the bird for the first time and managed to get a useable photograph, as well as several sound recordings.

Viaje ornitológico por Camboya junto a Luis Mario Arce y el guía local Chea Seab. Cuando abandonamos el hotel a las 5:35 h el termómetro marcaba unos agradables 18º C debido a la altitud. Fue de las pocas veces en que no sentimos la presión del sofocante calor tropical durante el viaje. Durante la jornada el termómetro se movería entre los 18º y 34º C, lejos de los 40º C que sufrimos en las tierras bajas. Condujimos unos 20 km en dirección suroeste para llegar a un sector protegido del bosque de Seima a las 6:15 h. A la luz del día pude comprobar que nos encontrábamos en una zona montañosa, bastante ondulada, en donde alternaban teselas de bosque bien conservado con teselas de terreno afectado por la deforestación. Tras desayunar en las sencillas, pero agradables, dependencias del Seima Protected Forest (SPF), iniciamos un recorrido por el interior del bosque (Lowland broadleaved evergreen forest) a las 6:35 h acompañados por un guía local. Se trataba de un bosque con al menos tres estratos arbóreos, presencia de numerosas plantas escandentes y manchas de bambú. En el primer tramo del recorrido vimos una pareja de Plain Flowerpecker y escuchamos el reclamo de Green-legged Partridge, aunque no conseguimos verlas. A partir de entonces nos centramos en buscar una de las dos especies de pitas que habitan en este bosque, la Bar-bellied Pitta. Tras localizarla por su  reclamo, conseguimos ver fugazmente los dos miembros de una pareja moviéndose por la parte baja del bosque. Rastreando con los prismáticos conseguí ver una hembra relativamente bien, aunque sólo durante un par de segundos. Cuando continuamos nuestro paseo escuchamos el reclamo de la segunda especie de pita que buscábamos --(Blue-rumped Pitta), aunque no conseguimos verla. Otras especies de notable interés vistas en el bosque fueron el casi endémico Red-vented Barbet, Great Iora, Black-and-buff Woodpecker o Swinhoe's Minivet.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Una pareja presente en el interior del bosque de Seima la mañana del día 29/3, consiguiendo ver bien durante un segundo a la hembra, característica por las tonalidades anaranjadas de su plumaje.

This is our Sam Veasna Trip with the clients from Hong Kong, Mr. Kelvin Ku and Ms. Angel Ho. There is a 3 days trip, which starts from the 25th of January 2018 till 27th January 2018. On the 26th Jan 2018, we visited Ang Trapeang Thmor known as the Sarus Crane Reserve Area. We began by driving from Siem Reap town toward Benteay Mean Chey around one hour then turn to the Phnom Srok Area. On the way we saw four Sarus Cranes, Eastern and Pied Harrier and with some of the Owls, such as Spotted Owlet, Asian Barred Owlet, Common Barn Owl, and Spotted Wood Owl. We only spent the short morning, as we were going to camp in the forest of Varin (Chong Kran Roy) at the same day. When we left Ang Tropeang Thmor we then continued to the Northern Part of Siem Reap where we were camping in the bush. This area is called, Chong Kran Roy, in Varin District. We actually got our beautiful species, Bar-bellied Pitta and with many other forest birds. This trip lead by Mr. Mardy Sean with an ID 29131801. For more info please contact our website: www.samveasna.org.
SPECIES COMMENTS: This adorable species came to our hide around 4:30PM and stayed nearly an hour feeding and bathing at the waterhole which arranged by Chong Kran Roy Community.

CHECKLIST COMMENTS: Drove and then walked to Crocodile Lake from HQ. Jonathan Eames accompanied me

From dawn to lunchtime we visited Loc Tri sub-district and a valley called Khe Don, leading to a low pass 4-5km SSE of the HQ area. The pass was at 410-420m asl. Secondary forest began at c.100m asl., and steadily improved up to the pass. Looked bad from a distance, but good inside. The trail we took was along an old logging road, from when the area was commercially logged after the war, for a few years around 1980. We met 100-150 people going up to the pass (and up to 2 hours farther on, and down into Quang Nam Province). They were collecting pieces of cut timber (worth c.7-10,000 Dong each), which were being bought by a furniture store; each worker being hired for 3,000 Dong. Relatively little cutting was going on within park limits, but still a fair amount.
Walked up to KM 8, then down into and across valley along former forest trail
Walked up to KM 8, then down into and across valley along former forest trail

Birding alone, but with Jonathan Eames, Nguyen Cu & Truong Van La, during our second expedition to Vietnam. An impressive thunderstorm 0400-0500, with lightening and some rain. The roof leaked. Mostly clear bright day with rain 1300-1500. Walked west and south from our base for c.3km, following river into pass between hills, towards Quang Binh border. Went out briefly to the north of the village in the evening.

Walked in a loop from our base for c.5-6km through an area of good to excellent secondary forest to the NW. We were accompanied by a local hunter (Le Xuan Can) and his two dogs. He showed us an area where he had often seen L. hatinhensis (syn. of Edwards's Pheasant) and another area where his dogs had flushed one two weeks earlier. In the afternoon visited another area with Blyth's KF etc.

Suoi Trai Hang. In morning followed ridge south of the camp, along logging road until it crosses stream at c. 350m asl. & shortly after followed a ridge down to the NW. In afternoon crossed river from camp and followed logging road up to stream at c.325m & 225m asl.
Khe Ao. Followed the Kheo Ao via logging road until at c.400m elevation and not far below the furthest point we visited from Suoi Trai Hang last year.

Leading Regulus tour group from Sweden, with Urban Olsson. "In morning took trail through U-shaped valley to its end, then up and over and down the other side." This was the site of the re-discovery of Sooty Babbler the previous year. This site is in the middle of the area that is now surrounded by the familiar park road system, being roughly 3-4km SW of the East Entrance Guard Post and to the S or SSW of Phong Nha Cave. We camped just inside the park somewhere, near the East Entrance.

Dong Nai Culture and Nature Reserve - camp two
CHECKLIST COMMENTS: I walked down the road to the west (ca. 6 km from the junction with our road). At ca. 4 km the scrubby forest became Eucalyptus groves. In one grove there were greater than 20 Garrulax leucolophus and 5 G. monileger foraging on the ground, flipping leaves with their bills. I also audio recorded at least 4 Black-shanked Doucs (Pygathrix nigriceps) -- fantastic look at a male that responded to playback. Hung Le picked me up at 0915. Hot and sunny again. Audio recordings deposited at Cornell Lab of Ornithology.--Results from this work were published:--Le Manh Hung, M.B. Robbins, N.H. Rice, E. A. Garcia-Trejo, S.M. Roels, and S.A. Bodbyl-Roels. 2011. Preliminary survey of the avifauna at Dong Nai Culture and Nature Reserves, Dong Nai province,Vietnam. Forktail 27:114-117.

CHECKLIST COMMENTS: I went quit a bit faster on the way back, but did spend some time tolling for Red-vented Barbet and Bar-bellied Pitta. OTHER FAUNA: One brihgt turquoise-headed lizard ('dragon') was sunning in a small clearing on the way out and the way back. Two days of birding in Cat Tien NP. My driver, Hoang, graciously met me at the hotel at 3:00 am and got us to the ferry dock at 6:00 am. I birded on foot that day to the Forest Floor Lodge about 1 km west of the headquarters, then back aong the forest trails to the HQ, and then back to the lodge. Feeling ill, I took a 2 hour nap and then did afternoon birding from the deck and then west and south along the pavement. After a fitful night of sleep, the next day I got a (very expensive) ride to the Crocodile Lake trailhead, hiked in 5 km, and then birded along the lakeshore. On my way out I finally scored my first Vietnam pitta, and then hiked back along the main road since my driver was late. I finally departed at 15:30 (without my passport), but we quickly looped back and recovered the crucial document and headed on to Da Lat. Butterflies throughout were phenomenal, with some great concentration puddling on roads and the edges of Crocodile Lake. With my camera out of comisson for part of the stay, I didn't document their variety well. WEATHER: Warm (80-90 F), calm, with occasionally afternoon showers.
SPECIES COMMENTS: *lifer; good but obscured and challenging looks at one bird that responded with a song. I stalked it through the undergrowth (only barely keeping my bearings for the return to the trail), and got a few looks as it walked away. A second bird was heard singing shortly thereafter, but an Emerald Dove sighting was all I got from that one.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Had a good look at a nice male and heard several others.

It took Mr. Tien and me over an hour to get just a glimpse of this bird. He played a recording as we stole around in the forest, and the bird responded, coming closer and closer. Mr. Tien never saw the bird. I saw only the head of the female, but there were probably two birds here. The bird had a warm, pale-brown head and crown, with a bold blackish ear patch.

These birds surprised us, especially after the hard time we'd had yesterday --getting even a glimpse. They were walking on the trail ahead of us, and --stayed in view for ten to fifteen seconds. This time I had good looks at the --blue on the tail, the green crown of the male, the barring on the undersides, --etc. The head of the female was exactly like the bird I saw yesterday.

Field Guides Inc. 2025 Vietnam tour with guides Doug Gochfeld and Lê Quý Minh.--Hiked out to Crocodile Lake and back, with a delicious lunch at the lake. Weather was real nice on the way out. The first section of the return hike was hot and sweaty, but it got better when we were under better forest cover, and snacks helped.--Several controlled burns put a whole lot of ash in the sky for periods of half an hour or so, but then the sky cleared. We saw the flames from one of the burns / quite impressive!!--Other animals included Northern Smooth-tailed Treeshrew, Black-shanked Douc Langur, and, of course, Siamese Crocodile.

CHECKLIST COMMENTS: With Jan Jaap Brinkman

With Jan Jaap Brinkman. Great to see the pair of Blue-eared Kingfishers! We also has close contact with three Bar-bellied Pittas, who were calling loudly in response to our tapes, but unfortunately not yet seen...Two lifers for me!
SPECIES COMMENTS: Clearly heard at close distance, reacted to playback recorded sounds. See attached sound recordings of several Bar-bellied Pittas calling with a White-rumped Shama in the background.
